sts - unavoidable security checks, etc. - <br />&gt; hardware costs.<br /><br />Yes. One thing to look out for on x86 is the system call _return_ path. It <br />doesn't show up in kernel profiles (it shows up as user costs), and we had <br />a bug where auditing essentially always caused us to use 'iret' instead of <br />'sysret' because it took us the long way around.<br /><br />And profiling doesn't show it, but things like lmbench did, iret being <br />about five times slower than sysret.<br /><br />But yes:<br /><br />&gt; -ENTRY(system_call_after_swapgs)<br />&gt; +.globl system_call_after_swapgs<br />&gt; +system_call_after_swapgs:<br /><br />This definitely makes sense. We definitely do not want to align that <br />special case.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
